properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain, strong winds and storm surge conditions early in the week. The Gaspé Peninsula and the North Shore will receive 50 to 80 millimetres of rain between Monday night and Wednesday. Rainfall amounts could even reach 100 millimetres over some localities of the tip of the Gaspé Peninsula and the Lower North Shore. Strong east winds will combine with the poor weather conditions and could cause breaking sea conditions in some areas. The heavy rain may cause flash floods and ponding on roads. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A strong Pacific frontal system moving across the B.C. South Coast this morning will give potentially damaging winds. For Metro Vancouver, Southern Gulf Islands, Sunshine Coast - Gibsons to Earls Cove and communities in the mouth of Howe Sound, including Bowen Island, the south to southeast winds up to 60 km/h will veer sharply to the northwest 40 to 60 km/h with gusts up to 70 this morning. The winds will abate near noon as the front moves inland. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall expected today into Wednesday. Total snowfall amounts of 20 to 40 cm are possible. Precipitation is expected to begin this morning as rain or snow and change to snow this afternoon. Snowfall amounts of 10 to 20 cm are possible by Tuesday morning. Additional snowfall amounts of 10 to 20 cm are a possibility Tuesday through Wednesday morning, Strong northerly winds gusting near 70 km/h are also possible tonight and Tuesday, particularly near Lake Huron or Georgian Bay. This snowfall is a result of a strengthening low pressure system expected to move through eastern Ontario into Quebec Tuesday into Wednesday. Precipitation associated with this low pressure system is expected to move east of the area by Wednesday. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A long episode of heavy rain is expected. Maximum rainfall amounts: 80 to 130 mm, except possibly exceeding 150 mm in the extreme southwestern region of the province. Locations: most of southern and central New Brunswick. Time span: this evening through Wednesday afternoon. Remarks: A slow moving, intense low pressure system will move into New England later today and into Quebec on Wednesday. Rain ahead of this system will begin this evening and become heavy over most areas tonight. Heavy rain bands will continue to move over the province over the next couple of days, before easing off on Wednesday afternoon or early evening. At this time, rainfall amounts are expected to be heaviest in the southwestern portion of the province. Here, rainfall amounts of 100 to 130 mm are possible by Tuesday evening with additional significant amounts likely on Tuesday night and into Wednesday. The total rainfall amount may exceed 150 mm by Wednesday afternoon. For central New Brunswick, areas of the Fundy Region east of the Saint John River, and the Kennebecasis Valley, total rainfall amounts of 70 to 100 mm are likely, with amounts possibly exceeding 120 mm in some areas. Similar rainfall events in the past have caused road washouts and localized flooding in low-lying areas. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.
